{"parentUuid":"76701f7b-aab8-4f50-8508-e25ac2ff4ae6","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"23c7e5a1-fea1-44da-b966-2af678afb6e5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012pv1HdDx4vk9SC4JsmXyuo","type":"tool_result","content":"Shell cwd was reset to /Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"6fffca16-4e1e-4e7c-a2d4-87f885454637","timestamp":"2026-04-30T09:38:49.273Z","toolUseResult":{"stdout":"","stderr":"\nShell cwd was reset to /Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"76701f7b-aab8-4f50-8508-e25ac2ff4ae6","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","sessionId":"5b613073-e70b-48a1-b6ae-c6aaa99ec2b1","version":"2.1.121","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
{"parentUuid":"6fffca16-4e1e-4e7c-a2d4-87f885454637","isSidechain":false,"attachment":{"type":"edited_text_file","filename":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/gitsync/README.md","snippet":"1\t# git-sync\n2\t\n3\t`git-sync` mirrors refs from a source remote to a target remote without creating a local checkout. It uses an in-memory `go-git` object store and talks smart HTTP directly:\n4\t\n5\t- `info/refs` ref advertisement for source and target\n6\t- `upload-pack` fetch from source with target tip hashes advertised as `have`\n7\t- `receive-pack` push to target with explicit ref update commands and a streamed packfile\n8\t\n9\tThat keeps the target side incremental without fetching target objects into the local process first.\n10\t\n11\t## Why This Exists\n12\t\n13\tMirroring Git data between remotes usually means a local mirror clone followed by a mirror push. That's fine for small repos but turns a remote-to-remote operation into a local storage problem at scale, and shell glue around `git fetch` / `git push` tends to skip planning and structured output.\n14\t\n15\t`git-sync` fills that gap. It streams source packs directly into target `receive-pack` when it can, plans every action before pushing, and emits typed JSON for automation.\n16\t\n17\tFor when to use it (and when not), see [docs/architecture.md](docs/architecture.md).\n18\t\n19\t## Commands\n20\t\n21\tThe main commands are:\n22\t\n23\t- `git-sync sync`: mirror source refs into the target\n24\t- `git-sync replicate`: overwrite target refs to match source via relay, and fail rather than materialize locally\n25\t\n26\t`sync` automatically bootstraps an empty target, so the same command covers initial seeding and ongoing sync. To preview what would happen without pushing, run `git-sync plan` — it takes the same flags as `sync`, and `--mode replicate` previews a `replicate` run.\n27\t\n28\tFor command examples, JSON output, auth, protocol flags, and advanced command notes, see [docs/usage.md](docs/usage.md).\n29\t\n30\t## Library API\n31\t\n32\t`git-sync` is also a Go library. Use `entire.io/entire/gitsync` for the stable embedding surface (`Probe`, `Plan`, `Sync`, `Replicate`, typed results, auth and HTTP injection). `entire.io/entire/gitsync/unstable` exposes advanced controls (`Bootstrap`, `Fetch`, batching knobs, heap measurement) and is not stable.\n33\t\n34\t## Installation\n35\t\n36\tRequires Go 1.26 or newer.\n37\t\n38\tInstall the latest release with `go install`:\n39\t\n40\t```bash\n41\tgo install entire.io/entire/gitsync/cmd/git-sync@latest\n42\t```\n43\t\n44\tThis drops a `git-sync` binary into `$(go env GOPATH)/bin`. Make sure that directory is on your `PATH`.\n45\t\n46\tOr build from source:\n47\t\n48\t```bash\n49\tgit clone https://github.com/entireio/git-sync.git\n50\tcd gitsync\n51\tgo build -o git-sync ./cmd/git-sync\n52\t```\n53\t\n54\t## Quick Start\n55\t\n56\t```bash\n57\tgit-sync sync \\\n58\t  --source-token \"$GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN\" \\\n59\t  --target-token \"$GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN\" \\\n60\t  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n61\t  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n62\t```\n63\t\n64\t## Sync Behavior\n65\t\n66\t`sync` picks the bootstrap relay path automatically when the target is empty. For non-empty targets, safe fast-forward updates also use a relay path that streams the source pack directly into target `receive-pack` without local materialization. Anything not relay-eligible (force, prune, deletes, tag retargets) falls back to a materialized path bounded by `--materialized-max-objects`.\n67\t\n68\tFor branch filtering, ref mapping, tags, pruning, protocol selection, JSON output, and auth details, see [docs/usage.md](docs/usage.md).\n69\t\n70\t## Testing\n71\t\n72\tDefault suite:\n73\t\n74\t```bash\n75\tenv GOCACHE=/tmp/go-build go test ./...\n76\t```\n77\t\n78\tExtended and environment-specific test instructions are in [docs/testing.md](docs/testing.md).\n79\t\n80\t## Documentation\n81\t\n82\t- [docs/usage.md](docs/usage.md) — CLI commands, examples, sync behavior, JSON output, auth, protocol notes\n83\t- [docs/architecture.md](docs/architecture.md) — product rationale, package layout, operation modes vs transfer modes, memory model\n84\t- [docs/protocol.md](docs/protocol.md) — smart HTTP, pkt-line, capability negotiation, sideband, relay framing\n85\t- [docs/testing.md](docs/testing.md) — test suites and integration coverage\n86\t\n87\t## FAQ\n88\t\n89\t### Does it sync complete Git history or only perform a shallow/partial sync?\n90\t\n91\t`git-sync` syncs the complete Git object history required for the selected refs. It does not create a shallow clone. Some planning paths may use filtered fetches, but the target receives the full objects needed for valid refs.\n92\t\n93\t### Is it just refs, or objects as well?\n94\t\n95\tObjects as well. Refs are what `git-sync` plans and updates, but it also transfers the commits, trees, blobs, and tags needed for those refs to exist on the target.\n96\t\n97\t### Is it bidirectional?\n98\t\n99\tNo. `git-sync` is one-way: source remote to target remote. To go the other way you'd run a second invocation with the endpoints swapped.\n100\t\n101\t### Does it support create, update, and delete actions?\n102\t\n103\tYes. It supports creating refs, updating refs, force updates with `--force`, and deleting managed refs with `--prune`. `replicate` can overwrite target refs, but it is relay-only and more restrictive than `sync`.\n104\t\n105\t### How does it scale?\n106\t\n107\t`git-sync` has two transfer paths:\n108\t\n109\t- **Relay** — pack data streams from source `upload-pack` directly into target `receive-pack`. The local process holds no object graph, so memory stays bounded regardless of repo size. Used when the target supports relay.\n110\t- **Materialized fallback** — when relay isn't available, `git-sync` fetches the needed objects into an in-memory `go-git` store, plans, then encodes and pushes a packfile. Memory scales with the diff being pushed and is guarded by an explicit object-count limit. Bootstrap can batch large initial syncs to keep this bounded.\n111\t\n112\tPlanning itself is cheap: ref-only round-trips, plus a `filter tree:0` fetch for ancestry checks when the source advertises filter support.\n113\t\n114\t### How long does it take for a medium-sized repo?\n115\t\n116\tIt depends on repository size, network speed, and whether the relay path is available. As a rule of thumb, the relay path is bounded by source pack generation + network transfer + target receive-pack time — roughly the time of a `git clone` from the source plus a `git push` of the same pack. The materialized fallback adds local memory work for objects that need inspection.\n117\t\n118\tFor concrete numbers on your own setup, run the included benchmark tool against a representative repo; see [docs/testing.md](docs/testing.md#benchmarking).\n119\t\n120\t### Does it support SSH?\n121\t\n122\tNo. `git-sync` supports smart HTTP/HTTPS only.\n123\t\n124\t### Is this one-time or does it run in the background?\n125\t\n126\t`git-sync` is a one-shot CLI/library operation. It does not run as a daemon or background watcher. Run it manually, from CI, cron, a worker, or another service.\n127\t\n128\t## Contributing\n129\t\n130\tSee [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md), [SECURITY.md](SECURITY.md), and [CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)."},"type":"attachment","uuid":"7f2d4586-7ec0-4e68-a2b8-8789041def5c","timestamp":"2026-04-30T09:38:49.283Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","sessionId":"5b613073-e70b-48a1-b6ae-c6aaa99ec2b1","version":"2.1.121","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
